{"id":"0805.1619","submitter":"Stephane Regnier","authors":"S. Regnier, E. R. Priest","title":"Free Magnetic Energy in Solar Active Regions above the Minimum-Energy\n  Relaxed State","comments":null,"journal-ref":"The Astrophysical Journal, 2007, Volume 669, Issue 1, pp. L53-L56","doi":"10.1086/523269","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  To understand the physics of solar flares, including the local reorganisation\nof the magnetic field and the acceleration of energetic particles, we have\nfirst to estimate the free magnetic energy available for such phenomena, which\ncan be converted into kinetic and thermal energy. The free magnetic energy is\nthe excess energy of a magnetic configuration compared to the minimum-energy\nstate, which is a linear force-free field if the magnetic helicity of the\nconfiguration is conserved. We investigate the values of the free magnetic\nenergy estimated from either the excess energy in extrapolated fields or the\nmagnetic virial theorem. For four different active regions, we have\nreconstructed the nonlinear force-free field and the linear force-free field\ncorresponding to the minimum-energy state. The free magnetic energies are then\ncomputed. From the energy budget and the observed magnetic activity in the\nactive region, we conclude that the free energy above the minimum-energy state\ngives a better estimate and more insights into the flare process than the free\nenergy above the potential field state.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 12 May 2008 12:25:16 GMT"}],"update_date":"2008-05-16"}
